ohha.puzzlecrafter.puzzles

Class Puzzle

  • java.lang.Object
    • ohha.puzzlecrafter.puzzles.Puzzle
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    Fillomino, Sudoku

    public abstract class Puzzle
extends Object
    Represents a general puzzle to be extended by concrete puzzle styles. It is an abstract class instead of an interface so that it can host the fields common to all puzzles, and offer default implementations where possible.

      • setValues

        public void setValues(List<Integer> values)
        Sets the full selection of possible values the puzzle's cells may take in the solved puzzle. All values but Grid.UNDETERMINED_CELL are permitted here. This restriction isn't enforced here, however.

        Compare to getCandidates(CellCoordinate), whose purpose is to supply a possibly filtered selection of possible values for a certain cell.

        Parameters:
        values - the list of values the cells of the puzzle may take

      • getValues

        Returns:
        the full list of values the puzzle's cells may take

      • getCandidates

        public List<Integer> getCandidates(CellCoordinate c)
        Returns a possibly pruned selection of values the cell at the given coordinate may take, considering the puzzle's state. This method is provided so that concrete puzzle implementations have a way of weeding out clearly unsuitable values by overriding it. No pruning is required, but the implementations mustn't filter out genuine candidates.

        Compare to getValues(), whose purpose is to supply the full selection of values that are permitted in the puzzle.

        Parameters:
        c - the coordinate of the cell whose possible values are requested
        Returns:
        a list of feasible values that may go into the given cell

      • setCell

        public void setCell(CellCoordinate c,
                    int value)
        Fills the given value into the cell at the given coordinate. This is the intended method for the solver to fill the grid with. Compare to setGiven(CellCoordinate, int), whose purpose is to insert pre-filled values as hints to the solver.

        Givens may not hold the value Grid.UNDETERMINED_CELL. If this method is asked to set that value, it won't.

        Parameters:
        c - the coordinate of the cell to fill
        value - the value to fill in

      • cycleValueOfCell

        public void cycleValueOfCell(CellCoordinate c,
                             int amount)
        Cycles the value in the cell at the given coordinate by the given amount. This method isn't intended to be used by the automated solver, as it also assigns to cells the value Grid.UNDETERMINED_CELL.
        Parameters:
        c - the coordinate of the cell whose value to cycle
        amount - the amount of steps to cycle

      • setCellUndetermined

        public void setCellUndetermined(CellCoordinate c)
        Sets a cell's value to Grid.UNDETERMINED_CELL. This method is intended to be used when the solver resets a cell's contents, instead of setCell(CellCoordinate, int) and setGiven(CellCoordinate, int), which will fail if trying to assign an undecided.
        Parameters:
        c - the cell whose value to reset.

      • setGiven

        public void setGiven(CellCoordinate c,
                     int value)
        Sets the given value into the cell at the given coordinate as pre-filled information to the solver, like the already filled-in numbers in Sudoku. This is the intended method for the puzzle writer to set pre-filled values with. Compare to setCell(ohha.puzzlecrafter.grid.CellCoordinate, int), which is the method the solver will use to fill the grid with.

        Givens may not hold the value Grid.UNDETERMINED_CELL, and if this method is used to set a given cell undetermined, nothing is done.

        Parameters:
        c - the coordinate of the cell to set as a given
        value - the value to set in

      • setAsGiven

        public void setAsGiven(CellCoordinate c)
        Sets the cell indicated by the coordinate as a given, unless it is undetermined. This method only changes the 'given' status of a cell, but not its contents. For the latter, see setGiven(ohha.puzzlecrafter.grid.CellCoordinate, int).
        Parameters:
        c - the coordinate of the cell to set as a given

      • setGivens

        public void setGivens(List<CellCoordinate> givens)
        Sets the given list of coordinates as givens for the puzzle. This method is only intended for the use of deepCopy(), and does not check whether the cells are undetermined or not.
        Parameters:
        givens - the list of coordinates to set as givens

      • getGivens

        public List<CellCoordinate> getGivens()
        Returns the coordinates of givens (pre-filled values) in the grid. This enables the solver not to overwrite these cells. Givens must not be the value {ohha.puzzlegrafter.grid.Grid#UNDETERMINED_CELL}.
        Returns:
        a list of coordinates of cells with givens

      • getStartingCell

        public CellCoordinate getStartingCell()
        Returns the first cell to start the iteration from. The default implementation simply starts from the top left corner, moving row by row from top to bottom, looking for the first non-given cell. Concrete puzzle implementations may override this method to provide a more efficient sequence of cells that results in detecting futile efforts earlier and thus triggering backtracking earlier.

        If this method is overridden, the method getNextCell(ohha.puzzlecrafter.grid.CellCoordinate) must also be overridden to make sure that the solver tries every cell.

        Returns:
        the cell for the solver to start from

      • getNextCell

        public CellCoordinate getNextCell(CellCoordinate c)
        Returns the next undetermined cell for the solver to try, or null if there is none. The default implementation simply moves row by row from top to bottom. Concrete puzzle implementations may override this method to provide a more efficient sequence of cells that results in detecting futile efforts earlier and thus triggering backtracking earlier.

        It is important that any implementation makes sure all the cells of the grid are covered.

        If this method is overridden, the method getStartingCell() must also be overridden to make sure that the solver tries every cell.

        Parameters:
        c - the cell last modified by the solver
        Returns:
        the next cell intended for the solver to modify

      • isPartialSolution

        public abstract boolean isPartialSolution(CellCoordinate c)
        Returns true if the current state of the puzzle is possible to be completed into a full solution, that is the state of the puzzle is not in contradiction with the puzzle's rules. This method must be implemented case by case in each puzzle.

        The passed parameter is the coordinate of the cell where the solver last filled a value, as it is most often sufficient to check that the rules of the puzzle still hold only around the cell that changed.

        Parameters:
        c - the cell last modified by the solver
        Returns:
        true if the puzzle may be completed into a valid solution, false otherwise

      • deepCopy

        public abstract Puzzle deepCopy()
        Returns a deep copy of the puzzle. This method allows the solving algorithm to copy the solved puzzle into a list of solutions, and then further mutate the puzzle object it is solving.

        It must be implemented by each concrete puzzle implementation so that it captures all the additional structures each puzzle might have, and that the puzzle object has the correct subclass. Regrettably this seems to result in a lot of copied code.

        Returns:
        a deep copy of the puzzle
